AstraZeneca (Overweight; Price Target: 14,000p)

We see an attractive outlook for Astra with significant re- rating potential given the very rich line- up of pipeline readouts, strong near/medium/long- term growth outlook, and undemanding valuation. We see Astra offering a HSD 2026- 29 EPS CAGR, driven by strong topline growth, particularly in Oncology, as well as new product launches, fueled by the late stage pipeline as well as an operating margin expansion story. We believe the market still overly heavily risk- adjusts the late stage pipeline and we see de- risking having the potential to drive a significant re- rating, as the market gains confidence in Astra hitting its \(\) 80bn\(2030 Revenue aspiration.

We set our Dec- 26 PT at a \(17.5\times 2026\mathrm{ECorePE}\) \(30\%\) premium to the EU large cap Pharma sector including Novo, implying a Dec- 26 PT of 140, justified by Astra offering a faster medium- term growth outlook (2026E- 29E EPS CAGR of \(8\%\) vs. Sector at \(5\%\) ) and a stronger longer- term growth outlook, given the richer pipeline.
Galderma (Overweight; Price Target: CHF160.00)

We rate Galderma Overweight and believe the company offers an attractive play on the fast growing skin- care market, combined with a strong EBITDA margin expansion story. We see sustained double- digit top- line growth, driven by the strong growth outlook for the overall Derma market (aesthetic consciousness, aging, rising middle class income, self- care) and Galderma's focus on the high growth sub- segments: (i) Injectable Aesthetics, (ii) Derma Skincare and (iii) Therapeutic Dermatology. We also see the top line receiving a significant boost from the biologic therapy 'Nemluvio', FDA approved for the skin diseases PN (Prurigo Nodularis) and AD (Atopic Dermatitis), where we see multi- blockbuster peak sales potential ( \(2.1bn 2030 Revenues). In addition to a strong top- line outlook, we forecast 500bps of EBITDA margin expansion 2023- 27, as Nemluvio switches from a significant drag to a tailwind, and we forecast Galderma delivering a 20% EBITDA CAGR 2026- 29, with further strong growth beyond.

We set a SFr160 Dec- 26 PT, based on 24x 2027E (30x 2026E) EV/EBITDA, justified by a 15% 2027- 30 EBITDA CAGR (20% 2026- 29 CAGR), with further strong growth beyond 2030, from Injectable Aesthetics and Derma Skincare. Our SFr160 PT is underpinned by our c.SFr160 NPV, which ascribes a 5% post 2029 terminal to Injectable Aesthetics, 4% terminal for Derma Skincare, and 0% terminal for Therapeutic Derma ex Nemluvio.

Grifols (Neutral; Price Target: €12.00)
With Grifols now seemingly set to remain a public company (the Brookfield take- private having gone quiet), we see a new market focus on fundamentals.

On the positive side, over the last year : (i.) corporate governance has improved, (ii.) the company has a new CEO and CFO, (iii.) financial disclosure has improved and (iv.) focus on FCF generation has increased.

On the more cautious side: (i.) the company is still highly levered (JPMc 4.9x 2025E ND/ EBITDA), (ii.) competitive threats to the IG and AAT franchises remain, (iii.) FCF generation improvement is still uncertain, and (iv.) there is still significant refinancing to be done in 2027.

Should the medium- term guide be delivered (2024- 29 7% Revenue CAGR, 10% EBITDA CAGR, and €3.5- 3.75bn of FCF generation), we believe shares look undervalued; however, we continue to still see some execution and competitive risk, hence our Neutral rating.
We set €12/\\$10 Dec- 26 Voting/Non- Voting PTs, set at 9x 2026E EV/EBITDA, NV shares maintaining the current c.25% spread.

Our 9x 2026 EV/EBITDA multiple is a 50% discount to EU mid- cap pharma peers on 17x, reflecting our forecast for Grifols to deliver a 7% 2026- 29E EBITDA CAGR, vs. Mid- cap peers at a greater than 16% CAGR.

Recordati (Overweight; Price Target: €67.00)

We are Overweight Recordati, given the strong growth outlook in 2025 (15% Revenue growth, 12% EBITDA growth, 15% EPS growth) and medium- term (2025- 30 Revenue CAGR of 5%, EBITDA CAGR of 6%, EPS CAGR of 8%). In addition we like the lack of patent expiry headwinds, due to the business model (SPC is post LOE, Rare disease assets face limited competition) and the low US exposure (only 18% of Revenues), which insulates the company from potential US tariff and Most Favoured Nations pricing headwinds.

We set a Dec- 26 €67 PT, set at 19x 2026E PE. A 19x 2026 Core P/E is broadly inline with high growth European Specialty Peer UCB, though a premium to Generics peers such as Hikma and Sandoz, on c. 10x/12x respectively, which we see as fair, given Recordati's more stable long- term outlook.
Sandoz (Overweight; Price Target: CHF46.00)
We view Sandoz as an attractive play on global Generics and Biosimilars, with Biosimilars benefiting from high barriers to entry and a strong growth outlook.

We forecast \(4\%\) 2026- 29 Revenue CAGR, which, combined with 2.5pp of 2026- 2029E EBITDA margin expansion (+ve mix on GM, operating leverage & stand- alone efficiency), leads us to forecast Sandoz to deliver \(7\%\) EBITDA 2026- 29E CAGR and \(9\%\) Core EPS CAGR.

We see three key reasons to own: (1.) Upside risk on the Revenue outlook of MSD CAGR 2023- 28, which could prove conservative; (2.) Upside risk on EBITDA margins, where guidance only calls for a recovery back to 2020 levels by 2028, but where operating leverage and efficiencies could offer upside; and (3.) Valuation, where shares trade at only 8x 2026e EV/EBITDA, which we see undervaluing the company's strong long- term growth outlook.

Our SFr 46 PT is based on 10x 2026E EV/EBITDA, a 1.5x turn premium to where we set our Hikma PT, justified by Sandoz's faster medium- term growth, and greater medium- term visibility, with Sandoz having issued guidance out to 2028.
Our Sandoz PT multiple is a premium to US peers Teva and Viatris (c.6x 2026 EV/EBITDA currently), which we see as justified by faster medium- term growth and greater biosimilar exposure.
Zealand (Overweight; Price Target: Dkr1,100.00)

We rate Zealand Overweight, given the promise of its broad Obesity pipeline, in particular "Petre", an amylin therapy, which could offer similar weight loss to GLP- 1s such as Wegovy, but with the advantages of: (1.) better tolerability (2.) Improved body composition.

We estimate that c. \(20\%\) of Obesity/Diabetes patients cannot tolerate incretins, which could create a c. \(535\mathrm{bn}\) additional opportunity for alternatives such as amylins, where we see Petre taking \(\%\) of this sub- market, offering c. \(510\mathrm{bn}\) potential peak sales. Based on encouraging Phase Ib data, we see a good chance of Zealand partnering Petre by the end of '25, which could provide both a valuable upfront, and validation from a Large Cap Pharma company, who will then support Phase III development, commercialisation and manufacturing. Even applying just \(50\%\) POS to Petre (LA Amylin), \(70\%\) POS to SurvO (a GLP- 1/Glucagon) which is already partnered and in PIII, and \(20\%\) POS to Dapi (GLP- 1/GLP- 2), we calculate a Dkr1,100 NPV, the basis for our Dkr1,100 Jun- 26 PT.

We value Zealand using an NPV approach and calculate a c.DKr1,100 NPV, the basis for our Dkr1,100 Jun- 26 PT. Key contributors to our NPV are: (1.) Petre, where we model \(50\%\) POS of \(\) 10bn\(peak sales shared with a partner; (2.) SurvO, where we model\) 70\% \(POS of a\) 4bn peak sales asset, noting the asset is already in Phase III, and is partnered with BI; and (3.) Dapi, where we model \(20\%\) POS of a \(\) 4.0bn\(peak sales asset, our more cautious POS reflecting the early development stage and lack of a partner. We also include smaller product sales, anticipated R&D and central SG&A, plus the c.\) \ \(1.3bn\) of Net Cash.

Novo, Lilly, Astra and Gubra are also developing Amylin monotherapies. There is very little competitor data available to date, but it is possible that competitors also develop strong molecules, and these competitor molecules could represent future competition.- Setbacks for other pipeline assets. Petre accounts for \(c.75\%\) of our NPV, with Cash a further \(c.1\%\) , but it is possible that the remaining \(c.25\%\) of our NPV that comes from other pipeline assets could see setbacks, particularly if Survo Phase III data is below expectations, or Dapi disappoints in Phase II.
Genmab A/S (Neutral; Price Target: Dkr 1,500)

Post the JNJ HBCD38 opt- in decision, we now see the investment case hinging on Epkinly and Rina- S development. We see both assets having significant promise, however we note the lack of significant newsflow in the remainder of 2025 (we see Epkinly 2L DLBCL success as already expected), with Rina- S refractory Ovarian cancer Phase III data not until H2'26, and 1L DLBCL Epkinly data not until late '26. In addition, with time we also move closer to the 2029/30 US/EU end of Darzalex royalties from JNJ. With limited newsflow in the remainder of '25, and with our updated NPV derived PT offering only modest upside, we therefore remain Neutral.
We set a Jun- 26 PT of Dkr1,500/share, based on our Dkr1,500 NPV, equating to c.10.5x 2026 EV/EBITDA.

GSK PLC (Underweight; Price Target: 1,400p)

We see 2025 and 2026 as fairly quiet for GSK with only modest pipeline optionality, with new launches unlikely to drive significant upgrades, and with the company moving closer to the stat of the HIV patent cliff in 2028. On pipeline, the only notable Phase III readout is campixant for cough, now not until H2'26. GSK does still have an important regulatory decision, whether GSK approves Blenrep for multiple myeloma by the Oct \(23^{\mathrm{rd}}\) PDUFA. We ascribe \(50\%\) POS on approval, noting the negative ODAC vote, but also the fact that GSK has filed further undisclosed clinical data post the ODAC, and noting GSK's public confidence in still gaining approval. On launches, in 2025, we will be following (i. )Pennenvy combined Meningitis vaccine, (ii.) Nucala for COPD, (iii). and Blujepa for UTIs, followed in 2026 by depemokimab for Asthma, which could have a faster launch, but where much of the sales will come from cannibalising Nucala for Asthma. Though GSK's valuation is undemanding, with no consensus upside, and limited pipeline or other catalysts in '25E or '26E, we see little that can re- rate shares, and hence we remain relative UW, vs. peers with faster growth and/or greater pipeline optionality in '25. We set a Dec- 26 PT of £14.00.

We value GSK on a \(8\times 2026\mathrm{E}\) Core PE, the basis for our £14.60 Jun- 26 PT. Our target multiple is a c. \(30\%\) sector discount, justified by GSK offering a 6pp slower growth outlook from 2026- 29E (GSK: \(- 1\%\) CAGR, sector \(+5\%\) CAGR) given the dolutegravir loss of exclusivity in 2028.
Hikma Pharmaceuticals (Overweight; Price Target: 2,500p)

Over the next 18 months, we see a re- rating story for Hikma to \(9.2x\) 2026E EV/EBITDA, driven by: (1) continued strong growth for Injectable Revenues \((+8\%)\) in \(^{,}25\) and \(^{,}26\) and and Branded Revenues \((+7\%)\) in \(^{,}25\) and \(+8\%\) in \(^{,}26\) and (2) resilient performance in Generics (flat in \(^{,}25\) , MSD down in \(^{,}26\) ), but with potential return to growth as pipeline comes through. We also see potential upside optionality from new launches, most notably: (i) gVictoza w/in the Injectables division; (ii) Injectables capacity expansion allowing faster growth; and (iii) potential upside in Generics from further gAdviar share gains. We also see Hikma's clean BS (c.1x 2025 ND/EBITDA) offering scope for further BD.

We set a Dec 2026 PT of 25.00, set at 9.2x 2026E Group EV/EBITDA, putting Injectables on \(9x\) 2025E EV/EBITDA, Branded on \(10x\) and Generics on \(8x\) , forecasting a \(7\%\) EBITDA CAGR 2026- 29.
These multiples compare to closest EU peer Sandoz, currently trading on c. \(10x\) 2026E EV/EBITDA, for a \(9.5\%\) 2026- 29E EBITDA CAGR.
Oxford Nanopore (Overweight; Price Target: 190p)

We rate Oxford Nanopore at Overweight. In 2025, we expect ONT performance to be driven by operational execution on expansion into Biopharma and Clinical/Applied use of Nanopore sequencing, which should improve confidence in ONT's ability to achieve their mid- term targets and drive a re- rating. We expect ONT to deliver a strong year of operational performance, with \(22\%\) LC underlying Revenue growth and c. 150bps yoy Gross margin expansion to \(59\%\) . Given continued market concerns over ONT's 2025 outlook amidst sequencing peers' profit warnings, we expect execution of \(>22\%\) Revenue growth and 150bps of Gross margin expansion to improve confidence in ONT's ability to achieve their mid- term targets for a \(>30\%\) 2024- 27 Revenue CAGR, \(>62\%\) Gross margin in 2027 and Adj. EBITDA breakeven in 2027.
